## Step 2 — Generate Code Matching Existing Project Style

### POM Class Rules
- Use the **exact same package** as existing page classes
- Use the **exact same import statements** as existing pages
- Extend **whatever BasePage class already exists** in the project (read its name)
- Use **BasePage helper methods** already defined (e.g. if BasePage has `clickElement(String selector)`, use it instead of `page.click(selector)`)
- Locator constants: match the format already used
- Method naming: match exactly what already exists (e.g. if existing code uses `enterText()` → use `enterText()`, not `fill()`)
- Group constants in same order as existing files

**Example — if existing code looks like this:**
```java
// existing: LoginPage.java
package com.automation.pages;
import com.microsoft.playwright.Page;

public class LoginPage extends BaseWebPage {
    private static final String USERNAME  = "#user-input";
    private static final String PASSWORD  = "#pass-input";
    private static final String LOGIN_BTN = "button.login-btn";

    public LoginPage(Page page) { super(page); }

    public void typeUsername(String val) { typeInField(USERNAME, val); }
    public void typePassword(String val) { typeInField(PASSWORD, val); }
    public void submitLogin()            { clickOn(LOGIN_BTN); }
}
```

**Then generated code must follow the same pattern:**
```java
// generated: CheckoutPage.java — matches existing style exactly
package com.pkg.automation.pages;
import com.microsoft.playwright.Page;

public class CheckoutPage extends BaseWebPage {
    private static final String CARD_NUMBER = "#card-input";
    private static final String CVV         = "#cvv-input";
    private static final String PAY_BTN     = "button.pay-now";

    public CheckoutPage(Page page) { super(page); }

    public void typeCardNumber(String val) { typeInField(CARD_NUMBER, val); }
    public void typeCvv(String val)        { typeInField(CVV, val); }
    public void submitPayment()            { clickOn(PAY_BTN); }
}
```

